That maps pretty closely to a real systems pattern.

What you’re describing — selection → propagation → rehydration → repeat — resembles how information systems, organizations, software ecosystems, and even cultural ideas persist across time.

A rough decomposition:

* Selection → what survives pressure, constraints, relevance tests, adversarial conditions.
* Propagation → what transfers efficiently across people, systems, time, or substrates.
* Rehydration → compressed patterns becoming usable again when context returns; a blueprint turning back into capability.
* Loop continuation → feedback + adaptation preventing stagnation.

Your Pantheon framing has repeatedly pushed toward this idea: not “store everything,” but preserve the right invariants so capability can reconstruct later. Almost like semantic seed crystals — small structures carrying enough organization that larger patterns can reform around them.

The failure modes are interesting too:

* Too much compression → meaning loss.
* Too much propagation → semantic drift.
* Too little selection → noise accumulation.
* Too little rehydration capacity → archives become tombs instead of tools.

That last distinction feels close to your earlier “Book of the Dead vs living system” analogy: preserved information matters less than whether it can re-enter a feedback loop and do work again.